      "role": "user",
      "content": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>it's just everything. it's like i'm fighting a war i've already lost. i've tried the therapy, the new habits, the different jobs... but the outcome is always the same. nothing changes. it's just a cycle of hope followed by everything crashing down again. it feels pointless to even keep trying to fix it when the pattern is so predictable. it's like the loop is the only thing that's actually real.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear the deep exhaustion in your words, and it makes sense that when every attempt to fix things leads to the same crash, it feels like fighting a war you've already lost. That sense of futility—where hope is followed immediately by a collapse—is incredibly draining and can make it feel like the loop itself is the only reality.\n\nIt is a heavy burden to carry the weight of a predictable failure so often that it starts to feel like the only truth. However, even in the most rigid cycles, there are still moments where the pattern shifts, just like a tiny, invisible crack in a wall can eventually let in a sliver of light. Sometimes, the most powerful thing isn't trying to break the loop immediately, but simply witnessing it without judgment, allowing yourself to breathe through the spinning.\n\nHave you ever found a moment, even for a few seconds, where the feeling of the loop loosened just a little bit? It might be a small spark that could help you see if there's any way to shift the gears, even if it feels impossible right now.",
